WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.960
Continuing on with our machine learning explainable AI data science track, we are

00:00:04.960 --> 00:00:09.960
keeping in the theme of kind of containing LLMs and so please give Joe

00:00:09.960 --> 00:00:13.040
Cheng a warm welcome.

00:00:16.840 --> 00:00:20.959
Thanks. This has been a really great track so far. I actually feel like this

00:00:20.959 --> 00:00:24.000
will be a really nice compliment to Hugo's talk if you if you just got to

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.320
see that. Although there may be fewer f-bombs in this one. Although, fuck, fuck,

00:00:30.320 --> 00:00:37.639
fuck. Okay, now we're even. And fuck, now I'm up by one. So when I talk about LLMs

00:00:37.639 --> 00:00:42.720
today, I'm not talking about chat GPT. I'm not talking about co-pilot. I think like

00:00:42.720 --> 00:00:49.119
Hugo, I'm here to talk about more DIY LLMs. So building custom things that are

00:00:49.119 --> 00:00:53.639
designed for a more specific purpose. And if you are in this room and you are

00:00:53.639 --> 00:00:57.840
curious about LLMs but you have not built these kinds of things yourself, we

00:00:57.840 --> 00:01:02.320
have a package called chat lists that makes it very easy to get started

00:01:02.320 --> 00:01:08.120
building things using LLMs. We've tried to make this as simple as as possible to

00:01:08.120 --> 00:01:12.879
get started. So this is all you need to ask your first question to, in this case,

00:01:12.879 --> 00:01:18.120
Cloud 3.7 Sonnet. And if you want to proceed to building agents, you can do

00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:22.120
that too. There's all sorts of nice little bells and whistles that I'm not

00:01:22.120 --> 00:01:26.120
really going to get into today because the focus of today is going to be

00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:32.559
slightly different. But I do want to make it clear that if you are in this room, if

00:01:32.559 --> 00:01:38.279
you know Python, you are ready to harness LLMs to create advanced agents and you

00:01:38.279 --> 00:01:43.559
could do this today. But the question that I have is, should you? Like, is this

00:01:43.559 --> 00:01:49.519
actually a good idea? And to explain what this means to me, I work at Posit

00:01:49.519 --> 00:01:55.120
Software, PBC. I was the first employee 16 years ago. This company means a lot to

00:01:55.120 --> 00:01:58.919
me and it is a public benefit corp. And if you're not familiar what that means,

00:01:58.919 --> 00:02:03.080
you can think of it as sort of blending elements of nonprofit and for-profit

00:02:03.080 --> 00:02:07.639
organizations. And in order to be a public benefit corp, like a nonprofit, you

00:02:07.639 --> 00:02:12.160
need to have, as part of your corporate charter, a mission, a public benefit. And

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:16.520
for us, this is abridged, but it's to create open source software for data

00:02:16.520 --> 00:02:20.160
science, scientific research, and technical communication. And for us,

00:02:20.160 --> 00:02:25.119
that's in the form of Python packages, tools that are for data science, for

00:02:25.119 --> 00:02:29.720
research, and for communication. And I want to focus in on data science and

00:02:29.720 --> 00:02:33.559
scientific research specifically. I'm going to say data science a bunch of

00:02:33.559 --> 00:02:38.520
times today. And whether you self-identify as a data scientist or not,

00:02:38.520 --> 00:02:43.679
if you are using code to understand data, then for the purposes of this talk,

00:02:43.679 --> 00:02:49.080
please consider yourself a data scientist. And when we started this

00:02:49.080 --> 00:02:54.720
company, because of that focus on data science and scientific research,

00:02:54.720 --> 00:02:58.600
there are some principles that are core to who we are as a company. I don't

00:02:58.600 --> 00:03:05.000
expect you to read this, but in this book by John M. Chambers, he says,

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:08.759
those who receive the results of modern data analysis have limited opportunity

00:03:08.759 --> 00:03:12.639
to verify the results by direct observation. Users of the analysis have

00:03:12.639 --> 00:03:16.320
no option but to trust the analysis, and by extension, the software that

00:03:16.320 --> 00:03:23.759
produced it. Meaning software that creates answers from data, it's not

00:03:23.759 --> 00:03:28.199
always obvious whether the results are correct. Both the data analyst,

00:03:28.199 --> 00:03:32.679
that's most of you presumably, and the software provider, that's me,

00:03:32.679 --> 00:03:36.039
therefore have a strong responsibility to produce a result that is trustworthy

00:03:36.039 --> 00:03:40.240
and, if possible, one that can be shown to be trustworthy. This obligation,

00:03:40.240 --> 00:03:43.279
I label the prime directive. That's how important he thought it was that he

00:03:43.279 --> 00:03:47.479
called it the prime directive, and that's a directive that we adopted as a

00:03:47.479 --> 00:03:52.160
company as well. And because we know that people are using our tools,

00:03:52.160 --> 00:04:00.199
our open source tools, for healthcare, for drug development, to influence public

00:04:00.199 --> 00:04:04.800
policy, epidemiology, therefore we know that the stakes are high.

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:07.119
And this is a comment made by a software engineer at Posit.

00:04:07.119 --> 00:04:13.679
I'm aware that if I make a mistake, bad things happen, death and other things.

00:04:13.679 --> 00:04:17.760
And, like, thinking concretely about what that means, fulfilling the prime

00:04:17.760 --> 00:04:23.279
directive, obviously we need our results to be correct. We want the methods of our

00:04:23.279 --> 00:04:28.720
analysis to be transparent, meaning they can be inspected, and the analysis needs

00:04:28.720 --> 00:04:34.200
to be reproducible. And this being SciPy, I don't need to explain why these are

00:04:34.200 --> 00:04:37.079
important, but I just want to make it clear this is where we are coming from

00:04:37.079 --> 00:04:42.679
as a company. When you combine these things, like, this to us, not just...

00:04:42.679 --> 00:04:45.239
These aren't best practices or recommendations. These are moral and

00:04:45.239 --> 00:04:50.200
ethical obligations. Combining them with LLMs, like, what are we even talking about?

00:04:50.200 --> 00:04:53.720
Like, on paper, this is a terrible idea, right? When it comes to correctness,

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:58.519
these LLMs are infamous for giving convincing but wrong answers.

00:04:58.519 --> 00:05:02.239
Nobody understands why these things do what they do. Even the people who come up

00:05:02.239 --> 00:05:06.480
with the architectures, even the people who train them, this is an empirical art,

00:05:06.480 --> 00:05:11.799
right? And they are inherently non-deterministic. Even the ones that let

00:05:11.799 --> 00:05:15.480
you set a random seed, the providers are all careful to say you are not guaranteed

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:18.600
to get the same results because of changes in hardware over time and software

00:05:18.600 --> 00:05:23.399
configuration and things like that. So there is no reproducibility here.

00:05:23.399 --> 00:05:27.920
So given this sort of clash of these important values and these sort of really

00:05:27.920 --> 00:05:33.799
terrible qualities of LLMs... And we've all seen this. Like, we've all seen...

00:05:33.799 --> 00:05:38.279
Here, draw an intricate piece of ASCII art. Here's an intricate piece of ASCII art

00:05:38.279 --> 00:05:45.720
of a wolf. Right? This GPT-40 Mini. And the interesting thing is, like,

00:05:45.720 --> 00:05:50.359
these LLMs, they're not bad. I mean, especially, like, the latest models,

00:05:50.359 --> 00:05:53.519
the latest and greatest models, they're not bad. They're just jagged, right?

00:05:53.519 --> 00:05:57.440
Like, you might expect that an LLM would be like this, where there are easy tasks

00:05:57.440 --> 00:06:02.000
that they really get right almost all the time. And as the tasks get harder and

00:06:02.000 --> 00:06:08.279
harder, they get worse and worse. And if you've used LLMs with any regularity,

00:06:08.279 --> 00:06:13.079
you know that this is not the world that we live in. LLMs are like this. Right?

00:06:13.079 --> 00:06:17.160
Like, there are easy things that they are awesome at, and there are easy things that

00:06:17.160 --> 00:06:20.279
they are surprisingly terrible at. And then there are hard things that they

00:06:20.279 --> 00:06:23.600
excel at, and then hard things that are almost the same as the thing that they

00:06:23.600 --> 00:06:27.320
excel at that they are terrible at. And, like, two points that I would highlight

00:06:27.320 --> 00:06:32.119
here is, like, they're really good at coding, and coding is super hard.

00:06:32.119 --> 00:06:34.279
I mean, we kind of take it for granted now because it's been, like,

00:06:34.279 --> 00:06:38.920
a year and a half. But especially the latest models, what they can do is jaw-dropping,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:42.480
if you stop and think about it. And yet, the very simplest of data tasks,

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:46.160
they will fall on their face. And if you are not convinced by that,

00:06:46.160 --> 00:06:52.040
I will show you. This is an example that I ran yesterday, just to be sure.

00:06:52.040 --> 00:06:56.440
So let's start with an array of random numbers using NumPy of some length n.

00:06:56.440 --> 00:07:00.760
We're going to vary this n over time. Okay? We're going to fire up chat list

00:07:00.760 --> 00:07:05.320
and ask GPT-4-1, which is OpenAI's latest and greatest general purpose model,

00:07:05.320 --> 00:07:08.600
how long is this array? And then we give it a JSON representation.

00:07:08.600 --> 00:07:14.320
I mean, what could be easier than len, right? And if we give it a length 10 array,

00:07:14.320 --> 00:07:19.600
it says 10. That's actually correct. Okay, good job. At 100, it gets it correct.

00:07:19.600 --> 00:07:25.079
At 1,000, it gets it correct. At 10,000, it gets it wrong. It says it's 1,000.

00:07:25.079 --> 00:07:30.640
Why there? Who knows? And this is actually, as disappointing as this is,

00:07:30.640 --> 00:07:35.079
this is already cherry-picking to make the model look good because I picked pretty

00:07:35.079 --> 00:07:40.640
round numbers. If I change it to 103, the LLM says 100. So we're talking

00:07:40.640 --> 00:07:44.320
about software that cannot tell you the length of an array. Like,

00:07:44.399 --> 00:07:50.000
what business do we have using this technology in data science?

00:07:50.000 --> 00:07:56.359
So are there ways that we can use this together? And about a year ago,

00:07:56.359 --> 00:08:02.279
me and my team, the Shiny team at Posit, decided to, like, let's just humor

00:08:02.279 --> 00:08:07.119
ourselves and give it a try and see what we could do if we made our best effort at

00:08:07.119 --> 00:08:12.600
making something useful with our technology in an LLM. And what we came

00:08:12.600 --> 00:08:16.040
up with is this. So this is a Dashboard. This is a Shiny Dashboard.

00:08:16.040 --> 00:08:19.959
If you haven't seen Shiny, it's a web framework that helps people

00:08:19.959 --> 00:08:23.880
who primarily just work with data create interactive web applications like this

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:28.079
without being web developers. And, you know, if you hide this part,

00:08:28.079 --> 00:08:31.279
all of this is just standard Shiny. Shiny has done this for years and years.

00:08:31.279 --> 00:08:36.359
It's not an LLM. It's just a terministic interactive code. And I can do things,

00:08:36.359 --> 00:08:39.719
like I can change options here to say, like, do I want to show the most common

00:08:39.719 --> 00:08:44.479
or least common birds? This is bird sighting data from the eBird dataset

00:08:44.479 --> 00:08:50.039
from Cornell. There's a map down here that I can pan and zoom that's folium.

00:08:50.039 --> 00:08:55.119
So all of that is pretty standard. And what we decided to do was to see if we

00:08:55.119 --> 00:09:00.520
could use an LLM to make this Dashboard more useful. On a lot of these Dashboards,

00:09:00.520 --> 00:09:04.119
you would expect to see a sidebar with our sliders and dropdowns that you can use

00:09:04.119 --> 00:09:07.479
to filter the data, and we decided to replace that with a chatbot.

00:09:07.479 --> 00:09:10.280
So here, I'm going to say, like, so this is bird sighting data.

00:09:10.280 --> 00:09:20.159
I'm going to say, like, show only observations between 6 a.m. and noon.

00:09:20.159 --> 00:09:28.880
Let's see, where the observation method is stationary. Okay, I spelled it wrong,

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:37.239
but I think it'll probably figure it out. All right. So it goes ahead and does

00:09:37.239 --> 00:09:42.719
that, including correcting my spelling there. And the important thing to note

00:09:42.719 --> 00:09:49.520
here is that although everything on here changed, this SQL here is the only thing

00:09:49.520 --> 00:09:54.440
that the LLM has direct control over. I'm not asking the LLM for answers.

00:09:54.440 --> 00:09:59.400
I'm asking it for SQL. Once it generates the SQL, everything else is handled

00:09:59.400 --> 00:10:03.640
by deterministic code. It's handled by Shiny. And very importantly,

00:10:03.640 --> 00:10:07.679
we display the SQL at all times. So on the off chance that it does make a

00:10:07.679 --> 00:10:11.760
mistake or something doesn't seem right to you, you only have to look up and see,

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:15.479
like, do I think that that looks correct? Yeah, that seems to be okay.

00:10:15.479 --> 00:10:21.039
And the same thing in the chat history here, we make sure to leave the SQL there

00:10:21.039 --> 00:10:26.919
so that you can refer back to it later. And this is a simple query that you could

00:10:26.919 --> 00:10:30.559
have done with sliders and dropdowns, but because this is natural language,

00:10:30.559 --> 00:10:33.359
it actually gives us the flexibility to do things we couldn't otherwise do.

00:10:33.359 --> 00:10:36.960
Like, I could say, like, invert the filter. So everything that you're showing now,

00:10:36.960 --> 00:10:43.039
hide and vice versa. And this is no longer something that is easy to do with most

00:10:43.039 --> 00:10:47.559
dashboarding frameworks. And I can go further and say,

00:10:47.559 --> 00:10:52.080
also show everything in this category, and it'll OR criteria together.

00:10:52.080 --> 00:10:56.559
You can ask it to calculate standard deviations and outliers and things

00:10:56.559 --> 00:11:01.559
like that. It'll do all those things. So besides filtering and sorting,

00:11:01.559 --> 00:11:05.239
you also have the ability to ask data questions. So you can say, like,

00:11:05.239 --> 00:11:08.479
we have the total sightings and total birds sighted here, but we don't have,

00:11:08.479 --> 00:11:16.919
like, what was the average and median counts of birds per sighting.

00:11:16.919 --> 00:11:20.559
And once again, this LLM, it actually doesn't even have access

00:11:20.559 --> 00:11:23.479
to the data. So it can't hallucinate based on the data.

00:11:23.479 --> 00:11:27.719
All it has access to is a data schema, and it will write SQL to answer this

00:11:27.719 --> 00:11:33.880
question. And here we can see. And for this particular application,

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:40.359
we also added these little buttons so that if it's not clear what you're seeing here

00:11:40.359 --> 00:11:44.359
in this visualization, you can press this button, and it'll send a screenshot

00:11:44.359 --> 00:11:50.159
of the output and ask the LLM what it sees. And interesting, like,

00:11:50.159 --> 00:11:56.799
in this case, it happens to notice that it seems to be following a river or

00:11:56.799 --> 00:12:00.080
waterway system, which I had not noticed despite looking at this many,

00:12:00.080 --> 00:12:08.599
many times. So this works pretty well. I mean, it works pretty well in terms

00:12:08.599 --> 00:12:11.280
of correctness because we are only asking it to generate SQL,

00:12:11.280 --> 00:12:15.280
which it does incredibly well. The best models today do that

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:20.080
incredibly well. It is transparent because every SQL query is displayed

00:12:20.080 --> 00:12:23.119
to the user, so you know how the answer is being derived.

00:12:23.119 --> 00:12:27.440
And it's reproducible because it's generating SQL, and SQL is reproducible.

00:12:27.440 --> 00:12:32.880
So it's almost magic how well SQL fits in at the intersection of what the LLM can

00:12:32.880 --> 00:12:38.159
write, what the code can execute, and what the human can review and interpret.

00:12:38.159 --> 00:12:42.359
So in fact, we were so happy with this approach that we made it a package.

00:12:42.359 --> 00:12:48.119
So if you're building a Shiny dashboard, it's like a four-line operation to drop

00:12:48.119 --> 00:12:53.640
in an LLM that does this kind of sidebar-based filtering.

00:12:53.640 --> 00:12:59.880
That package is called Query Chat. It's not on PyPI yet, but if you Google

00:12:59.880 --> 00:13:07.559
for it, you can find it. Now, that worked, and when I submitted

00:13:07.559 --> 00:13:11.799
the talk proposal, this is where the talk was supposed to end.

00:13:11.799 --> 00:13:15.640
A few months ago, we decided, just out of curiosity, like, yes, yes,

00:13:15.640 --> 00:13:18.119
we're a very responsible company. What happens if we let the LLM

00:13:18.119 --> 00:13:21.400
off the leash, right? Instead of, like, focusing in on these

00:13:21.400 --> 00:13:25.239
things that it can't do wrong, why don't we start with the best coding LLM

00:13:25.239 --> 00:13:30.840
at the time, CLAW 3.5 Sonnet, and we give it a tool to run Python

00:13:30.840 --> 00:13:36.200
unfettered and unsandboxed. And then we ask it data questions.

00:13:36.200 --> 00:13:40.359
So just this combination of things, what happens?

00:13:40.359 --> 00:13:43.400
Like, does it delete your hard drive or does it, like, you know,

00:13:43.400 --> 00:13:49.080
fulfill all of your wishes? So that, I'm going to show you an early

00:13:49.080 --> 00:13:52.280
prototype of something we so far have been calling Databot.

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:54.039
Everybody hates the name, so I'm sure we're going to change it

00:13:54.039 --> 00:13:58.280
before it sees the light of day. But I downloaded some data from 538,

00:13:58.280 --> 00:14:05.239
just some simple CSV data. So starting out in a directory,

00:14:05.239 --> 00:14:09.159
inside of this directory are a couple of CSV files and a readme,

00:14:09.159 --> 00:14:14.679
and then I launched Databot. And Databot is a simple chat bot

00:14:14.679 --> 00:14:19.960
that has the ability to execute Python. So it makes some suggestions,

00:14:19.960 --> 00:14:22.840
and I tell it, look in the current directory. I'm not even bothering it

00:14:22.840 --> 00:14:27.799
to tell it the name of these files. It sees that there's these three files,

00:14:27.799 --> 00:14:31.479
and then now it's making suggestions of what to do next.

00:14:31.479 --> 00:14:37.719
And what we're going to do is read the contents of the readme,

00:14:37.719 --> 00:14:42.520
and it reads it with just Python. And now it sees, okay, I can see this

00:14:42.520 --> 00:14:46.520
is NBA, this is basketball, historical game data.

00:14:46.520 --> 00:14:49.159
And it makes a suggestion again, like, let's load this data using

00:14:49.159 --> 00:14:55.400
pollers and look at what kind of data we're looking at.

00:14:55.400 --> 00:14:58.919
All right, so it's figured some things out. All of that is correct.

00:14:58.919 --> 00:15:02.599
And create a visualization showing the distribution of game scores.

00:15:02.599 --> 00:15:06.359
That seems like a pretty good place to start.

00:15:06.359 --> 00:15:10.280
So it's using the plot9 visualization package,

00:15:10.280 --> 00:15:15.159
and it's looking at the plot just like we are and coming to its own conclusions

00:15:15.159 --> 00:15:18.679
about what the data says. And we can look at the code.

00:15:18.679 --> 00:15:21.000
Everything is out in the open, so you can see all the code

00:15:21.000 --> 00:15:24.280
that generated the output.

00:15:28.280 --> 00:15:33.080
So this is where things go a little wrong.

00:15:34.039 --> 00:15:41.080
So there's an error in the code that it wrote, but like a good little agent,

00:15:41.080 --> 00:15:43.640
it realizes there was an error, and it wants to try again,

00:15:43.640 --> 00:15:47.719
and it tries again. And it generated the box plot.

00:15:47.719 --> 00:15:50.280
But interesting, I'm going to pause it here.

00:15:50.280 --> 00:15:56.840
There appears to be a trend towards higher scoring in recent seasons.

00:15:56.919 --> 00:16:03.479
But look at that box plot. Like, what are you talking about?

00:16:03.479 --> 00:16:06.200
So I was a little confused. I looked at the code.

00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:09.000
There was nothing obviously wrong. I mean, I looked at...

00:16:09.000 --> 00:16:10.840
This is real time. This is not sped up or slowed down.

00:16:10.840 --> 00:16:12.359
So that's how much time I looked at the code.

00:16:12.359 --> 00:16:18.760
And then finally, I was like... Sorry, the play bar is over, but I was like,

00:16:18.760 --> 00:16:21.479
what are you talking about? That's just one box.

00:16:21.479 --> 00:16:23.559
Yeah, that doesn't look right at all. There's a single box.

00:16:23.559 --> 00:16:28.599
It says, oh, let me see. Sorry, this data set only contains a single year.

00:16:28.599 --> 00:16:35.080
The other CSV file has all the other years. So let me go ahead and do that.

00:16:35.080 --> 00:16:37.080
And this time, it gets it right.

00:16:43.640 --> 00:16:47.479
But my biggest problem with this is that the X axis is super hard to read,

00:16:47.479 --> 00:16:49.880
because there's so many years smushed together.

00:16:49.880 --> 00:16:51.559
That's the kind of thing where I'm usually like,

00:16:51.719 --> 00:16:53.960
fine, I'll just make my window bigger or something.

00:16:54.599 --> 00:16:57.320
I can't be bothered to figure out how to fix it.

00:16:57.320 --> 00:16:59.719
But in this case, I just tell it, hey, I can't read it.

00:16:59.719 --> 00:17:03.080
Please fix it. And within seconds, it has fixed that.

00:17:17.319 --> 00:17:18.119
Yeah, much better.

00:17:18.839 --> 00:17:22.280
So the last thing here is...

00:17:23.719 --> 00:17:27.239
I mean, we have spent, what, a total of three minutes so far.

00:17:27.239 --> 00:17:30.680
But imagine that we were doing much more intense analysis,

00:17:30.680 --> 00:17:32.040
and we've learned all this stuff.

00:17:32.040 --> 00:17:34.680
And I don't want to forget all that just because my session ends,

00:17:34.680 --> 00:17:35.640
and I'm going to come back later.

00:17:36.439 --> 00:17:45.079
So what I'm telling it to do is basically take everything you've learned,

00:17:45.079 --> 00:17:49.000
summarize it, and put it in a file called llms.txt in the current directory.

00:17:49.640 --> 00:17:52.439
And then the next time I launch it, it immediately greets me with,

00:17:52.439 --> 00:17:56.280
hi, I have NBA data for you, and here are the things that I know about it.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:58.439
What questions do you want to ask me?

00:18:03.880 --> 00:18:09.479
So I did have to record that demo, because that demo can go very wrong,

00:18:09.479 --> 00:18:11.959
depending on what kind of answers you get back.

00:18:12.439 --> 00:18:14.839
But I swear, that was not cherry-picked.

00:18:15.719 --> 00:18:19.880
I ran that demo exactly one time today, recorded it, and that's what it was.

00:18:19.880 --> 00:18:22.520
And that's very typical for the kind of thing that happens.

00:18:22.520 --> 00:18:24.359
There are always mistakes in the code.

00:18:24.359 --> 00:18:26.439
It usually figures them out and fixes them.

00:18:26.439 --> 00:18:30.199
There are sometimes hallucinations where the plot is clearly wrong,

00:18:30.199 --> 00:18:33.479
and it says something confidently that it sees in the plot that it doesn't.

00:18:33.479 --> 00:18:36.920
But when the plot is right, it usually makes correct observations.

00:18:37.880 --> 00:18:41.079
So is this responsible?

00:18:41.079 --> 00:18:45.719
I mean, I feel really conflicted about this.

00:18:45.719 --> 00:18:50.040
I mean, on paper, this is violating so many best practices,

00:18:50.040 --> 00:18:56.280
both in terms of the prime director, but also in terms of security.

00:18:56.280 --> 00:18:58.199
But in practice, it is so effective.

00:18:58.199 --> 00:19:04.680
I mean, I can object intellectually, but I'll never do exploratory data analysis

00:19:04.680 --> 00:19:05.479
without this thing now.

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:12.680
That, you know, even though on paper there is this inherent tension,

00:19:13.400 --> 00:19:17.000
we have done some things to try to make it to mitigate the danger.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:20.760
We've limited it to exploratory data analysis only.

00:19:20.760 --> 00:19:23.880
We designed it for human intervention, so with tight feedback loops,

00:19:23.880 --> 00:19:27.160
so that humans are not overwhelmed by so many insights, they can't spot errors.

00:19:27.880 --> 00:19:32.839
We have UI tricks we use to try to make errors more visible to users.

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:40.280
And in practice, not writing the code, it's actually really easy for me to see

00:19:40.280 --> 00:19:42.520
when there are mistakes that the bot is making.

00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:45.640
Just like if you've ever paraprogrammed with someone and just been astonished

00:19:45.640 --> 00:19:47.719
at the simple mistakes they're making while they're typing,

00:19:47.719 --> 00:19:49.239
because you have all these cognitive,

00:19:50.199 --> 00:19:52.599
you have all these free brain cycles to look at their mistakes.

00:19:53.719 --> 00:19:57.800
So despite the conflict, we are going to ship a version of this in Positron,

00:19:57.800 --> 00:19:59.319
which is our next generation IDE.

00:19:59.319 --> 00:20:02.199
It is really advanced compared to what I just showed you.

00:20:02.199 --> 00:20:04.040
But we are going to call it a research preview,

00:20:04.040 --> 00:20:08.199
just because I still just feel really weird about this.

00:20:08.760 --> 00:20:11.400
And I really look forward to seeing what users do with this.

00:20:13.560 --> 00:20:17.239
The way I'm thinking about this now is not so much in terms of a black and white,

00:20:17.239 --> 00:20:20.680
are we doing things responsibly, or are we doing things not responsibly?

00:20:20.680 --> 00:20:23.959
Can this thing give correct answers, or can it not give correct answers?

00:20:23.959 --> 00:20:26.839
There are many dimensions here to this problem.

00:20:27.800 --> 00:20:32.199
And the two that I'll focus on in this unit list graph

00:20:32.199 --> 00:20:35.000
is likelihood of mistakes on the x-axis.

00:20:35.640 --> 00:20:38.760
So going towards the right means it's more likely to screw up.

00:20:39.560 --> 00:20:41.239
And then on the vertical axis,

00:20:41.239 --> 00:20:46.359
how likely are we to overlook those mistakes all the way to production

00:20:46.359 --> 00:20:48.920
or all the way to the conclusions of the analysis?

00:20:50.839 --> 00:20:54.359
So something like query chat is very unlikely to make a mistake.

00:20:54.359 --> 00:21:00.199
But if it does, you're probably not really on the lookout for a lot of mistakes.

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:04.359
So it's kind of middling in terms of how likelihood you are to find it.

00:21:04.359 --> 00:21:07.319
Something like data bot, you're encouraged to be much more vigilant,

00:21:07.319 --> 00:21:09.000
but it is more likely to make mistakes

00:21:09.000 --> 00:21:12.040
because it has much broader kind of tasks that it'll try to do.

00:21:12.760 --> 00:21:15.400
And then something like chat GPT's deep research mode,

00:21:15.400 --> 00:21:19.479
where you encourage it to go off and think for a long time about hard problems

00:21:19.479 --> 00:21:22.680
and then come back with reams and reams of conclusions.

00:21:22.680 --> 00:21:28.199
To me, unless you already knew the answer of the question that you're asking,

00:21:28.199 --> 00:21:31.640
it is almost impossible to find the subtle mistakes that it'll make.

00:21:31.640 --> 00:21:34.119
And anecdotally, the people I've talked to

00:21:34.119 --> 00:21:37.160
who really know the topics that they ask deep research about

00:21:37.160 --> 00:21:42.040
say it's pretty common for it to come back with 90% correct and 10% incorrect answers,

00:21:42.040 --> 00:21:44.359
which is almost like the worst ratio, right?

00:21:44.359 --> 00:21:48.359
Like that's just high enough for you to be lulled into a false sense of security.

00:21:49.000 --> 00:21:50.439
So what does this mean?

00:21:50.520 --> 00:21:54.760
Like where is your level of tolerance?

00:21:54.760 --> 00:21:58.199
And I think that really depends on who you are.

00:21:58.199 --> 00:22:00.439
It really depends on what you're doing.

00:22:00.439 --> 00:22:07.000
So if you are a data science consultant in marketing or something like that,

00:22:07.800 --> 00:22:09.479
maybe it's something like this.

00:22:09.479 --> 00:22:14.920
Maybe it's like everything below and to the left of that line is safe enough for you,

00:22:16.359 --> 00:22:19.160
where either it is unlikely to make a mistake

00:22:19.160 --> 00:22:21.239
or if it makes a mistake, you'll probably catch it.

00:22:22.119 --> 00:22:26.760
But if you are doing nuclear safety or something like that,

00:22:27.319 --> 00:22:28.599
maybe that line is down here.

00:22:29.160 --> 00:22:30.839
Like maybe almost nothing is good enough.

00:22:32.359 --> 00:22:36.599
And if you are a LinkedIn influencer, then maybe the line's over here.

